{
  "texts": [
    "Therefore, more efficient and effective energy-saving measures have to be pursued in the 6G network.",
    "As shown in Fig. 5, a 6G autonomous network must achieve \"zero touch, zero wait, and zero faults\" using four fully automated and intelligent processes: selfdeployment and configuration, self-optimization, selfhealing, and self-evolution during the entire lifecycle.",
    "Table 1 Energy and data efficiency comparison of 4G and 5G networks Status Peak power Average power (30% load) Minimum power (idle, 0 load) Equipment model (number of channels and the overall transmit power) 4G (8 and 120 W) 5G (16 and 240 W) 5G (64 and 240 W) 4G (8 and 120 W) 5G (16 and 240 W) 5G (64 and 240 W) 4G (8 and 120 W) 5G (16 and 240 W) 5G (64 and 240 W) Bandwidth (MHz) 60 160 * 160 * 60 160 * 160 * 60 160 * 160 * Power (W) (BBU+3AAU) 1100 3131 4297 722 1798 3039 560 1226 2500 Throughput (Mb/s) 120 1216 1963 36 364.8 589.8 0 0 0 Energy efficiency (J/bit) 1 0.278 0.238 2.188 0.538 0.562 * 4G included.",
    "For column \"Energy efficiency,\" the relative values to 4G mobile networks are presented.",
    "BBU: baseband unit; AAU: active antenna unit"
